A few months into building a MERN app, I hit a familiar wall.
One simple “user profile with recent posts” screen needed three separate REST calls — /users/:id, /users/:id/posts, /posts/:id/comments — stitched together on the client. Half the fields coming back weren't even used.
That’s usually the moment people start looking into GraphQL. Not because it’s trendy, but because REST starts costing you extra round trips once your data gets a little nested.
Here’s what GraphQL actually is, how it works under the hood, and when it’s worth reaching for.
What GraphQL Actually Is
GraphQL is a query language for your API. Instead of having a different endpoint for every shape of data you might need, you have one endpoint, and the client tells the server exactly what it wants back.
So instead of:
GET /users/1
GET /users/1/postsYou send one query like:
{
user(id: "1") {
name
email
posts {
title
createdAt
}
}
}And you get back exactly that — no more, no less. No extra fields that you don’t need, no second round trip to fetch the posts.
That’s really the core idea. Everything else is implementation detail.
How It Works Under the Hood
There are three pieces that matter: the schema, resolvers, and the query/mutation split.
1. The Schema
The schema is a contract. It defines every type of data your API can return and how those types relate to each other. Think of it as TypeScript interfaces, but for your entire API surface.
type User {
id: ID!
name: String!
email: String!
posts: [Post!]!
}type Post {
id: ID!
title: String!
createdAt: String!
author: User!
}Notice posts lives inside User, and author lives inside Post. That relationship is what lets you query nested data in a single request — the schema is what makes "user with their posts" a valid thing to ask for.
2. Queries vs Mutations

• Query = read data (like a GET)

• Mutation = write data (like POST/PUT/DELETE)
# Query - fetch a user and their posts
query {
user(id: "1") {
name
posts { title }
}
}# Mutation - create a new post
mutation {
createPost(title: "Hello GraphQL", authorId: "1") {
id
title
}
}That’s it. There’s no separate “endpoint” for mutations — same single endpoint, different operation type.
3. Resolvers
This is the part people misunderstand most. GraphQL is not a database, and it doesn’t magically know how to get your data. For every field in your schema, you write a resolver function — a small piece of code that says “here’s how to actually fetch this.”
const resolvers = {
Query: {
user: async (_, { id }) => {
return await User.findById(id); // MongoDB call via Mongoose
},
},
User: {
posts: async (parent) => {
return await Post.find({ authorId: parent.id });
},
},
};So when you query user { name posts { title } }, GraphQL calls the user resolver first, then calls the posts resolver using the result of the first one. It's resolvers all the way down. The architecture, end to end, looks like this:
Client (React)
→ GraphQL Server (Express + Apollo Server)
→ Resolvers
→ MongoDB / REST APIs / other servicesGraphQL is just a smart routing and shaping layer sitting in front of however you’re already fetching data.
A Small MERN Example
Here’s a minimal setup using Express, Apollo Server, MongoDB (Mongoose), and React — the actual MERN stack, with GraphQL replacing your usual REST routes.
Server side (Express + Apollo Server):
const { ApolloServer, gql } = require('apollo-server-express');
const express = require('express');
const mongoose = require('mongoose');
const User = require('./models/User');
const Post = require('./models/Post');const typeDefs = gql`
type User {
id: ID!
name: String!
posts: [Post!]!
}
type Post {
id: ID!
title: String!
}
type Query {
user(id: ID!): User
}
`;const resolvers = {
Query: {
user: (_, { id }) => User.findById(id),
},
User: {
posts: (parent) => Post.find({ authorId: parent.id }),
},
};async function start() {
const app = express();
await mongoose.connect('mongodb://localhost:27017/blog'); const server = new ApolloServer({ typeDefs, resolvers });
await server.start();
server.applyMiddleware({ app, path: '/graphql' }); app.listen(4000, () => console.log('Server ready at /graphql'));
}start();Client side (React, using Apollo Client):
import { useQuery, gql } from '@apollo/client';const GET_USER = gql`
query GetUser($id: ID!) {
user(id: $id) {
name
posts {
title
}
}
}
`;function UserProfile({ id }) {
const { loading, error, data } = useQuery(GET_USER, { variables: { id } }); if (loading) return <p>Loading...</p>;
if (error) return <p>Something went wrong</p>; return (
<div>
<h2>{data.user.name}</h2>
<ul>
{data.user.posts.map((post) => (
<li key={post.title}>{post.title}</li>
))}
</ul>
</div>
);
}One request. One hook. Exactly the fields you asked for. That’s the whole pitch, made concrete.
The Advantages

• No over-fetching or under-fetching. You get exactly the fields you asked for, nothing more.

• One request instead of many. Especially valuable on mobile or slow networks, where round trips are expensive.

• Strongly typed schema. It doubles as documentation, and tools like Apollo’s dev studio or GraphiQL let you explore the API interactively.
The Disadvantages (the part people skip)

• The N+1 problem. If you’re not careful, fetching 50 users and each of their posts means 50 separate posts resolver calls — 50 separate DB queries. You generally need a batching tool like DataLoader to avoid hammering your database.

• Caching is harder. REST gets HTTP caching almost for free (cache by URL). GraphQL’s single endpoint and flexible queries mean you need extra tooling (Apollo Client’s cache, persisted queries, etc.) to get similar benefits.

• More setup overhead. Schema design, resolver wiring, client-side cache config — there’s real upfront cost compared to slapping together a quick REST route.

• Overkill for simple APIs. If your app is just basic CRUD with one client, GraphQL adds complexity without solving a problem you actually have.
When to Use It, and When Not To
Use GraphQL when:

• You have multiple clients (web + mobile) with different data needs from the same backend

• Your data is deeply nested and REST forces you into multiple round trips

• Your frontend iterates quickly and you don’t want backend changes gating every UI tweak
Skip GraphQL when:

• You’re building a small CRUD app or internal tool

• Your data is flat and simple — REST already does the job with no pain
Wrapping Up
GraphQL isn’t a REST killer, and it’s not “the future of APIs” in some grand sense — it’s a tool that solves a specific, common pain: fetching exactly the data you need, in the shape you need it, without juggling a dozen endpoints. If that pain sounds familiar, it’s worth the setup cost. If it doesn’t, REST is still perfectly fine, and adding GraphQL on top would just be solving a problem you don’t have.
